  "text": "The Prometheus Alertmanager notification pipeline consists of several key components that work together to process and dispatch alerts:\n\n## Alert Ingestion\nAlerts enter the system through the HTTP API v2 endpoint implemented in api/v2/api.go. The postAlertsHandler (lines 313-373) receives alerts via POST /api/v2/alerts, validates them, and stores them in the alert provider using api.alerts.Put(). The handler converts incoming OpenAPI alert models to internal types.Alert objects.\n\n## Routing Tree Traversal\nThe dispatch/dispatch.go Dispatcher is the central orchestrator of the notification pipeline. It implements a subscription pattern by calling alerts.Subscribe() to receive incoming alerts. In the run() method (line 148), it iterates through each alert and uses d.route.Match(alert.Labels) to find all matching routes in the routing tree. The routing tree is defined in dispatch/route.go as a Route structure with hierarchical matching rules. Each matched route is passed to processAlert(), which determines the aggregation group for the alert and schedules notifications.\n\n## Inhibition Check\nThe inhibit/inhibit.go Inhibitor component evaluates inhibition rules to suppress notifications for target alerts when source alerts are firing. The Inhibitor.Mutes() method (line 127) checks if an alert's label set matches any inhibition rule's target side, and if the source alerts of that rule are currently active. Inhibition rules are defined with source and target matchers, and require matching label values specified in the Equal field. The inhibitor runs in the background to maintain a cache of active source alerts.\n\n## Silence Check  \nThe silence/silence.go Silencer component checks if alerts are silenced. The Silencer.Mutes() method (line 113) queries the Silences object for all active or pending silences that match the alert's label set. Silences are stored as protobuf messages with matchers that define which alerts they apply to, and include time windows during which they are active.\n\n## Notification Pipeline Stages\nThe notify/notify.go PipelineBuilder.New() method (lines 395-421) constructs a chain of notification stages that process each alert group before sending notifications. The stage chain includes:\n1. GossipSettleStage - waits for cluster consensus\n2. MuteStage with Inhibitor (line 408) - filters inhibited alerts\n3. TimeActiveStage - checks active time intervals  \n4. TimeMuteStage - checks mute time intervals\n5. MuteStage with Silencer (line 411) - filters silenced alerts\n6. Per-receiver stages created by createReceiverStage() (lines 424-447) for actual notification delivery\n\nEach Stage implements the Stage interface (line 243) with an Exec method that transforms the alert list and context as it passes through the pipeline.\n\n## Final Notifier Dispatch\nAfter passing through all stages, alerts reach the per-receiver integration stages. The createReceiverStage() function creates a FanoutStage that executes multiple receiver-specific pipelines in parallel. Each pipeline includes stages for deduplication, retry logic, and finally the actual Notifier.Notify() call to each integration (Slack, PagerDuty, email, etc.).\n\n## Integration Point\nThe complete pipeline is orchestrated in cmd/alertmanager/main.go (lines 400-526). The configuration coordinator builds the routing tree, receiver integrations, and inhibition rules. The Dispatcher is created with the routing tree and pipeline (line 495), while the Inhibitor and Silencer are created from configuration (lines 464-465). The pipeline is then passed to the Dispatcher, which executes it for each alert group that requires notification."
}

